@piiswrong one cannot directly use epoch_end callbacks because (1) you need to know the current metric on eval set and (2) need to maintain state variables for what was the best heldout so far and how many epochs have past since this best. You can get around this by storing state in 'aux_params' however.

@paipai880429 assuming you are still interested in a solution, here's one way to go about it:
1. In python/mxnet/model.py:fit(...) add argument for early-stopping (perhaps with a default value, e.g. something like 'early_stopping_epochs = 10').
2. Within "fit()" function, pass this early-stopping variable to sub-function '_train_multi_device' and update the header for '_train_multi_device' to accept it (like step 1).
3. Within '_train_multi_device', search for 'eval_metric.get()' used on the evaluation set. Use this value and the early-stopping value to implement the logic to figure out when to stop. Call mxnet.model.save_checkpoint() to save model, and return to terminate.

